<span id="freeTextContainer1843878139038159475">Huxley&apos;s writing is brilliant and a joy to read. The work is littered throughout with so much religious and philosophical allusions, which adds to the thoughtful depth. I found it to be quite fascinating. <br/><br/>However, his conclusions leave empty. Essentially, it&apos;s religion achieved through chemistry. And his conception of religion focuses purely on the subjective. It&apos;s no surprise that he refers to Eckhart, Boehme, and eastern philosophy so often; he looks only at the &quot;inner light&quot; rather than consi</span>
  <span id="freeText1843878139038159475" style="display:none">Huxley's writing is brilliant and a joy to read. The work is littered throughout with so much religious and philosophical allusions, which adds to the thoughtful depth. I found it to be quite fascinating. <br /><br />However, his conclusions leave empty. Essentially, it's religion achieved through chemistry. And his conception of religion focuses purely on the subjective. It's no surprise that he refers to Eckhart, Boehme, and eastern philosophy so often; he looks only at the "inner light" rather than considering an external objectivism.</span>
